cs.PL, cs.LO, cs.SE, cs.TY, cs.CC 

This paper is likely to belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category as it presents a new domain-theoretic model of object-oriented programming (OOP) that includes full class/type names information found in nominally-typed OOP. It also compares NOOP to other domain-theoretic models of OOP, which is a common topic in the PL community. 

It could also belong to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category as it discusses the semantics of OOP and presents a new model for analyzing nominally-typed OO programming languages. 

The Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category is also a possibility as the paper discusses the benefits of nominal-typing to mainstream OO developers and OO language designers. 

The Types (cs.TY) sub-category is relevant as the paper discusses type inheritance and subtyping in statically-typed OO programming languages. 

Finally, the Computation and Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category is a possibility as the paper presents a mathematical model for analyzing nominally-typed OO programming languages.
